{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20870"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20870"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13745"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80025"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12325"},{"type":"tags","id":"12693"},{"type":"tags","id":"12695"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus (HIV) can affect multiple organ systems, including the central nervous system (CNS). The neurological manifestations of HIV infection can range from mild cognitive impairment to severe dementia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathogenesis of HIV-associated neurological damage in the central nervous system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Indirect damage via viral products and inflammatory cytokines","Vascular occlusion leading to multiple small infarcts","Opportunistic infections without HIV presence in the CNS","Autoimmune reaction against myelin basic protein","Direct infection and destruction of neurones by HIV"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism of HIV-associated neurological damage is \u003Cstrong\u003Eindirect damage via viral products and inflammatory cytokines\u003C/strong\u003E. HIV does not directly infect neurones but primarily infects microglia (cells of the macrophage lineage) in the brain. The neurological damage occurs through indirect mechanisms including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EViral proteins (such as gp120 and gp41) that may be toxic to neurones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInflammatory cytokines (IL-1, TNF, IL-6) released by infected microglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENitric oxide induced in neuronal cells by viral proteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect infection and destruction of neurones by HIV\u003C/strong\u003E - Neurones are not directly infected by HIV; the virus primarily infects microglia in the CNS\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune reaction against myelin basic protein\u003C/strong\u003E - While HIV can cause neurological damage, it is not primarily through an autoimmune mechanism targeting myelin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpportunistic infections without HIV presence in the CNS\u003C/strong\u003E - HIV does enter the CNS, carried by infected T cells and monocytes, and establishes infection in microglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular occlusion leading to multiple small infarcts\u003C/strong\u003E - While vascular complications can occur in HIV infection, the primary mechanism of HIV-associated neurocognitive disorder is not vascular occlusion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical syndrome of CNS abnormalities caused by HIV is called HIV-associated neurocognitive disorder (HAND). The severity of neurologic symptoms often exceeds what would be expected from the observed neuropathologic changes, supporting the indirect damage mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["HIV can infect the central nervous system, primarily targeting microglia which are cells of the macrophage lineage.","HIV-associated neurocognitive disorder (HAND) is the clinical syndrome of CNS abnormalities caused by HIV infection.","Neurones are not directly infected by HIV; neurological damage occurs through indirect mechanisms involving viral products and inflammatory cytokines.","HIV is transported into the brain by infected T cells or monocytes that cross the blood-brain barrier."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; page 253."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T17:57:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T18:04:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13745"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12325"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Immunodeficiency disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-14T18:45:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T18:45:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12693"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Pathogenesis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-04-01T18:30:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T18:30:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12695"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-04-01T18:36:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T18:36:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12795"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-04-10T00:02:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-10T00:02:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"33079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/33079"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2025-04-01T18:36:31+10:30","userDetails":{"name":"Karan V